04266nam a22006255i 9780812298321DE-B159720220302035458.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||220302t20222022pau    fo  d z      eng d  a97808122983217 a10.9783/97808122983212doi  a(DE-B1597)590732  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  apaucUS-PA 7aLIT0110002bisacsh1 aBude, Tekla, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aSonic Bodies :bText, Music, and Silence in Late Medieval England /cTekla Bude. 1aPhiladelphia : bUniversity of Pennsylvania Press, c[2022] 4c©2022  a1 online resource (336 p.) :b11 bw halftones, 1 table  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aSound in History00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tAcknowledgments -- tIntroduction. Writing Sonic Bodies -- tChapter 1. Musica Celestis and Canor: Angelic Song in Speculative Music Theory and Rollean Mysticism -- tChapter 2. Touching Music: Walter Hilton, Angels’ Song, and Synaesthesia -- tChapter 3. Attending to The Boke of Margery Kempe -- tChapter 4. Music, Amicitia, and Carthusian Mystical Diaries -- tChapter 5. Piers Plowman, the Sound-Object, and the Singing Community -- tChapter 6. Disability, Music, and Chaucer’s Advental Bodies -- tCoda -- tAppendix. A Short Exposition of the Manuscripts in Chapter 4 -- tNotes -- tBibliography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aWhat is the body when it performs music? And what, conversely, is music as it reverberates through or pours out of a performing body? Tekla Bude starts from a simple premise—that music requires a body to perform it—to rethink the relationship between music, matter, and the body in the late medieval period.Progressing by way of a series of case studies of texts by Richard Rolle, Walter Hilton, Margery Kempe, Geoffrey Chaucer, William Langland, and others, Bude argues that writers thought of "music" and "the body" not as separate objects or ontologically prior categories, but as mutually dependent and historically determined processes that called each other into being in complex and shifting ways. For Bude, these "sonic bodies" are often unexpected, peculiar, even bizarre, and challenge our understanding of their constitutive parts.Building on recent conversations about embodiment and the voice in literary criticism and music theory, Sonic Bodies makes two major interventions across these fields: first, it broadens the definitional ambits and functions of both "music" and "the body" in the medieval period; and second, it demonstrates how embodiment and musicality are deeply and multiply intertwined in medieval writing. Compelling literary subjects, Bude argues, are literally built out of musical situations.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 02. Mrz 2022) 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / Medieval.2bisacsh  aCultural Studies.  aLiterature.  aMedieval and Renaissance Studies.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Pennsylvania Complete eBook-Package 2022z978311076767440uhttps://doi.org/10.9783/978081229832140uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780812298321423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780812298321/original  a978-3-11-076767-4  University of Pennsylvania Complete eBook-Package 2022b2022  aEBA_CL_LT  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_LT  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK